ution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Morin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Marcel, Lucien, Emile, Pierre, Andre, Normand, Gilles, Jacques, Fernand, Adrien, Gaetan.","French and Walloon: from a variant of the French personal name   Maurin  ; or a diminutive of   More   2, a nickname for a dark-skinned man. It is also found in England, as a surname of Huguenot origin. Compare   Moran  ,   Morang  ,   Morein  ,   Morong  ,   Morrin  , and   Morrow  .","Italian (northern): variant of   Morino  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Morain","meanings":["Irish: altered form of <b>Moran</b>.","French: variant of   Morin  ."]},{"name":"Maurin","meanings":["French: from a medieval personal name derived from the Latin name <i>Maurinus</i>, a derivative of <i>Maurus</i> ‘Moor’ (see   Mauro  ), which was the name of a 6th-century Christian martyr. This form of the surname is also found in Germany, Italy, and Slovenia (see below). Compare   Morin  .","Germanized or Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Mavrin</b>: from a personal name derived from the Latin name <i>Maurinus</i> (see above). In part, <i>Maurin</i> is a Gottscheerish (i.e. Gottschee German) surname, originating from the Kočevsko region in Lower Carniola, Slovenia (see   Kocevar  ).","Italian: rare variant of   Maurino  , a cognate of 1 above."]},{"name":"Morneau","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Lucien, Adrien, Emile, Gaston, Gilles, Henri, Herve, Hilaire, Laurent, Napoleon.","French: shortened form of <b>Morineau</b>, derived from   Morin  , hence a double diminutive of   More   2, a nickname for a dark-skinned man."]},{"name":"Morang","meanings":["Altered form of French   Morin  ."]},{"name":"Morein","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Donovan, Brigid.  Russian Vitaly, Gleb.","Altered form of French   Morin  . This surname is established in LA.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Móráin</b> (see   Moran  )."]},{"name":"Morong","meanings":["Altered form of French   Morin  ."]}]},{"name":"Muriel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Celtic origin (  see  Muireall   ). Forms of the name are found in Breton as well as in Irish and Scottish Gaelic, and in the form   Meriel   it was in use in the heart of England in the Middle Ages. The surname <i>Merrill</i> is derived from it. As <i>Muriel</i> it was at first used mainly in Scotland, but became more widely popular during the first half of the 20th century. Since then it has fallen from favour again."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Muriel de Morin was born in 1235, in Garboldisham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 2 sons with John 'le Clerk' de Pakenham. She died in 1270, in her hometown, at the age of 35."},"et":{"1235–1270":"1235–1270","1220–1269":"1220–1269","1250–1304":"1250–1304","1265–1305":"1265–1305","1305":"1305","1304":"1304","1269":"1269","1235":"1235","1265":"1265","1220":"1220","1250":"1250","about 1265":"umbes 1265","1270":"1270","Dersingham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Dersingham, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Pakenham Place, Kirby Mallory, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom":"L